  "html": "\u003cdiv id=\"readability-page-1\" class=\"page\"\u003e\u003cdiv data-alias=\"gutenberg-content__content\"\u003e\u003cp\u003eThe first season of \u003cem\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://tvline.com/t/mid-century-modern/\" id=\"auto-tag_mid-century-modern_1\" data-tag=\"mid-century-modern\"\u003eMid-Century Modern\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/em\u003e was always going to open with a funeral, but creators \u003ca href=\"https://tvline.com/t/max-mutchnick/\" id=\"auto-tag_max-mutchnick_1\" data-tag=\"max-mutchnick\"\u003eMax Mutchnick\u003c/a\u003e and \u003ca href=\"https://tvline.com/t/david-kohan/\" id=\"auto-tag_david-kohan_1\" data-tag=\"david-kohan\"\u003eDavid Kohan\u003c/a\u003e never expected it to also end with another.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\n\n\u003cp\u003eNow streaming, the \u003ca href=\"https://tvline.com/t/hulu/\" id=\"auto-tag_hulu_1\" data-tag=\"hulu\"\u003eHulu\u003c/a\u003e comedy begins with three gay best friends — Bunny (Nathan Lane), Jerry (Matt Bomer) and Arthur (Nathan Lee Graham) — moving in together after the loss of their group’s fourth member. Because they decide to reside in Bunny’s Palm Springs abode, the boys get his mother Sybil (\u003ca href=\"https://tvline.com/t/linda-lavin/\" id=\"auto-tag_linda-lavin_1\" data-tag=\"linda-lavin\"\u003eLinda Lavin\u003c/a\u003e) as a bonus roommate… until her sudden death from a heart attack in Episode 9.\n\n\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\n\n\u003cp\u003eThis, of course, was written in response to \u003ca href=\"https://tvline.com/news/linda-lavin-cause-of-death-alice-dead-obituary-1235394003/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\"\u003eLavin’s real-life death\u003c/a\u003e midway through production on the season. The process of writing Sybil’s death, as well as the characters’ response to it, is one Kohan recalls as being “terrifying. Just really, \u003cem\u003ereally\u003c/em\u003e terrifying.”\n\n\u003c/p\u003e\u003cdiv data-alias=\"cards__inner\" data-component=\"cards-related-content\" data-collapse-to-x